Contextualize per-world beats. The story has more than one hard dilemma, so its
forks nest: after the first point of no return the world splits, and every later
story moment was instantiated once per world — same dramatic function, genuinely
different context. The engine copied the structure; you write what each copy's
moment actually looks like in its world. Some beats below are instead de-ended
tails: they used to end the story, but a final fork now follows them — rewrite
them to settle their own question while leaving the remaining one open.

VISION: {{ vision.genre }}, {{ vision.tone }}. Themes: {{ vision.themes | join("; ") }}.

BEATS TO REWRITE:
{% for t in targets %}
{% if t.kind == "clone" %}
- {{ t.beat.id }} (in the world of {{ t.world }}): {{ t.beat.summary }}
{% for f in t.facts %}
  true here: {{ f.dilemma.question }} -> "{{ f.answer }}" ({{ f.consequences | join("; ") }});
  committed when: {{ f.committed_at }}
{% endfor %}
{% else %}
- {{ t.beat.id }} (no longer the ending): {{ t.beat.summary }}
{% for q in t.open_questions %}
  still unresolved after this beat: {{ q }}
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}
{% endfor %}

REQUIREMENTS:
- Rewrite every beat listed, exactly once, keyed by its full beat id.
- Keep each beat's dramatic function: the same moment, the same stakes, the same
  entities — recolored by what is true in its world. Do not add or remove events.
- Per-world copies of the same moment must genuinely differ: what the characters
  know, fear, and have lost differs between worlds, and the summary must show it.
- De-ended tails: resolve their own arc's immediate action, but end open — the
  unresolved question above is the story's climax and must still be live.
- 1-3 sentences per beat.
